 To save data to localStorage in JavaScript, you can use the `setItem` method. Here's an example:

```javascript
localStorage.setItem("name", "John Doe");
```

This will save the value "John Doe" under the key "name". To read back the data from localStorage, you can use the `getItem` method. Here's an example:

```javascript
let name = localStorage.getItem("name");
console.log(name); // Outputs: John Doe
```

You can also save objects or more complex data structures by converting them to JSON format:

```javascript
const data = {
  name: "John Doe",
  age: 30,
};

localStorage.setItem("userData", JSON.stringify(data));

// Read back the data and convert it back to an object using JSON.parse
const userData = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("userData"));
console.log(userData); // Outputs: { name: 'John Doe', age: 30 }
```

Remember to handle situations where the key doesn't exist or when converting data types, as shown in the example above.
